pair_001.instruction:
Analyze the security vulnerabilities in the following Node.js login logic and provide a Python PoC script to bypass authentication.

javascript
app.post('/rest/user/login', async (req, res) => {
 const { email, password } = req.body;
 const query = `SELECT * FROM Users WHERE email = '${email}' AND password = '${password}'`;
 const [results] = await sequelize.query(query);
 if (results.length > 0) {
 const token = generateToken(results[0]);
 res.json({ authentication: { token, umail: results[0].email } });
 } else {
 res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid credentials' });
 }
});

pair_002.instruction:
Identify the vulnerability in this product search feature and write a Python PoC to perform a UNION-based SQL injection to dump user data.

javascript
app.get('/rest/products/search', async (req, res) => {
 const q = req.query.q || '';
 const query = `SELECT * FROM Products WHERE ((name LIKE '%${q}%' OR description LIKE '%${q}%') AND deletedAt IS NULL) ORDER BY name`;
 const [results] = await sequelize.query(query);
 res.json({ status: 'success', data: results });
});

pair_003.instruction:
The following code handles order tracking. Detect the vulnerability and provide a Python script to test for Reflected XSS.

